h and Slovak; Sorbian (<b>Pěch</b> and <b>P'ech</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Petr</i> (Czech), <i>Pětš</i> (Lower Sorbian), and   Peter   (Slovak). This is also a Germanized form of the Upper Sorbian cognate <b>Pjech</b>.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>pech</i> (German <i>Pech</i>) ‘pitch, tar’, presumably a nickname for someone with exceptionally dark skin or hair, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who prepared, sold, or used pitch. This may in part also be the origin of a homonymic Polish, Czech, and Slovak surname (compare above and below)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Pêche was born in 1358, in Eynsford, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Pêche, was 26 and his mother, Ellen de Ferrers, was 24. He married Joan Hadley in 1380, in Eynsford, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 8 October 1412, in his hometown, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1358–8 October 1412":"1358–8. oktoober 1412","1358–1412":"1358–1412","1363–1409":"1363–1409","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1389–1439":"1389–1439","1332–1376":"1332–1376","1335–1360":"1335–1360","1363":"1363","8 October 1412":"8. oktoober 1412